title: For Sale:  Coleman 530 GI Pocket Stove B47 Single Burner Backpack/Camp Stove
postcontent:
Coleman G I pocket stove, model No. 530 that is dated B47 (1947). This stove comes with its container,  two piece aluminum case can be used as cooking or eating utensils. 
The nickel plating is in good condition but worn in a couple small spot as shown.  
On the outside on the burner frame are the directions for pumping the tank. The lighting instructions are on the turn valve, the turn valve is broken but works.
On the side of the tank is says – No. 530, Coleman, Made In USA, B47. 
The pump does work and holds pressure and air passes when valve is opened. May need some TLC but it overall great condition
I have not lit this stove, but it is a Coleman and parts are readily available. This stove and container are in very good, clean condition
$50.00 obo

History
During World War II, the U.S. government tasked Coleman to develop a compact stove for military use. The stove had to be lightweight, no larger than a quart-sized thermos bottle, burn any kind of fuel, and operate in weather from -60 to +125 °Fahrenheit. Within 60 days, Coleman came up with what became the G.I. Pocket Stove. Designated the Model 520 Coleman Military Burner, the stove first saw service in November 1942 when 5,000 of the stoves accompanied U.S. forces during the invasion of North Africa. Over 1 million of the stoves were produced for war use, where it won high praise in the field: Ernie Pyle ranked it "just behind the Jeep" in its usefulness.

By the end of the war, Coleman began production of a civilian version of the Model 520, designated the Model 530 and advertised as the G.I. pocket stove. The Model 530 was promoted by Coleman as the "perfect pal for hunting, fishing and camping trips" that would "slip easily into a hunting coat pocket, glove compartment of a car, or corner of [a] picnic hamper." The single-burner G.I. Pocket Stove was only manufactured between 1946 and 1949; afterwards Coleman did not manufacture another single-burner, non-military backpacking stove until 1972. Larger single-burner stoves continued production starting with the 500 Sportsters

I used a .308 rifle and a .223 at these plates at 36 and 50 yards. Ar500 is target material not to be used as body armor. This body armor with the 2 plates and the vest weighs a total of 12 pounds. title: For Sale:  STEYR MANNLICHER .40 cal. M-A1 & 5 mags! 3 15rd mags and 2 12rd mags
postcontent:
I am selling my Steyr M40-A1, 40 caliber pistol with 5 magazines for $550. Two of them are the factory 12-round magazines and three are 15-round S&W mags that still fit flush. If you are not familiar with this gun the first thing that you will notice is the trapezoid sights. They are a patented design that has been shown to offer faster sight acquisition while blocking less of the field of view.
 Three nice things about this gun, compared to the Glock are that it has a take-down lever (even easier that taking down a Glock), and there is a safety key (if you have kids in the house, you can lock the gun), it is quick to unlock, the key fits right in where the safety lever is located. The last thing is that it has a round-in-the-chamber indicator; It is a nipple on the back of the gun, just under the rear site. It doesn’t just show you that the gun is cocked; it indicates whether there is a bullet in the chamber. You can see it clearly, but even in the dark you can feel it.
 There is a rubber grip on the handle that I find very comfortable, but if it is not your thing it easily removable back to the original stock grip. 
 I cannot say enough good things about the company, Steyr. The gun functions flawlessly. The only reason that I have ever had to contact the company was the replace the key and the manual. They mailed me both, free of charge. It only took about a thirty-second call. So nice to have friendly, southern-people answering the phone and not a machine.
 The capacity is 16 rounds with the Smith and Wesson extended magazines. I am including 3 of them or the capacity is 13 rounds with the stock 2 magazines that I am also including.
 It weighs only 23 ounces, and has a 4 inch barrel. If you are into 9 millimeter you can convert it as simply as changing the barrel; that is the only difference.
 Here is a nice long YouTube video that goes into great detail.
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KznDgMxKqB4

 This is priced to sell so it will go fast. If you are interested call me at REDACTED and ask for Rowe. You can also message me on my FaceBook page www.facebook.com/49treasure

 I can sell this to any Mississippi resident hassle-free. If you can't show a Mississippi ID we have to have it registered for an out-of -state sale. The last that I checked it would be a $15 cost that would be added to the sale.

title: For Sale:  CARCANO SPORTER WITH AMMO, DIES, CASES, BULLETS
postcontent:
A very nicely done sporter carbine on a Carcano M1938 Short Rifle action.  This rifle was "sporterized" long ago by someone who knew what he was doing.  It has a very nice Fajen stock in good grade walnut, and the crude military sights have been replaced with a set of Williams open sights.  The barrel is 21" and the bore is bright and shiny.  The gun and the stock are in very good condition, with over 85% of the original metal finish and the stock sound and free of any significant dings or gouges.  It comes with two boxes (40 rounds) of Norma factory ammunition loaded with soft point bullets; a box of brand new Norma brass, and a bag of bullets in the correct 0.268" diameter.  This is about as nice a "loaner" or truck gun as you will find, not some beater that Bubba hacked in his basement in 1964.  The caliber (6.5x52 Carcano) is, like all the 6.5's, an outstanding hunting round for deer sized animals, and Norma ammunition is the best there is.  Included are also several of the 6-round "en bloc" clips this rifle uses (try finding these aftermarket!) and a set of brand new, never-used, Lee reloading dies.  You will get years of use out of this rifle.  It will also be a fine gun for a new hunter, as the recoil with the 6.5 is very mild.  A far better choice for a small-statured hunter or youth than any .243!  Contact me through armslist or my web site (www.nrvoutdoors.com) and I can send pictures, I have none to post at the moment.

Some of these rifles were made by Beretta: I haven't checked to see if this one was, but it's nicely finished and looks better than most of the stuff that came out of Italian government arsenals.
